        <h5>Maker-Taker Model Explained</h5>
        <p>Kraken uses a maker-taker model: makers (who add liquidity with limit orders) pay 0.16%, takers (who remove liquidity with market orders) pay 0.26%. This incentivizes limit orders which improve market quality. For comparison, Binance charges 0.1% flat (before discounts). On a $10,000 trade, you'd pay $16-26 on Kraken vs $10 on Binance. The difference: $6-16 per trade, which adds up for active traders.</p>

        <h5>Volume Discounts Available</h5>
        <p>Kraken offers tiered discounts for high-volume traders. $50K monthly volume gets you 0.14%/0.24%. $100K gets 0.12%/0.22%. The highest tier ($10M+ monthly) reaches 0%/0.10%. Realistically, retail traders won't reach these tiers, but active traders can reduce costs meaningfully. Check if your expected volume qualifies for better rates before committing.</p>

        <h5>Futures Fees: Where Kraken Competes</h5>
        <p>Kraken Futures fees (0.02% maker / 0.05% taker) are very competitive - matching or beating most competitors. If futures trading is your focus, Kraken's fees become more attractive. The spot premium essentially buys you a regulated, secure platform, while futures offer competitive pricing with the same security benefits.</p>

        <h5>Hidden Costs to Watch</h5>
        <p>Credit card deposits carry a 3.75% fee - avoid this by using wire transfers (free) or crypto deposits (free). Wire withdrawal fees ($4-35) depend on method and currency. Staking takes a 15% commission on rewards - higher than some competitors but includes the convenience of not running your own validator. Always calculate total costs including deposit/withdrawal, not just trading fees.</p>
