        <h4>Why Kraken's Security Matters</h4>
        <p>In crypto, security isn't just a feature - it's existential. The industry has seen billions lost to exchange hacks, exit scams, and insolvency. Kraken's security-first approach addresses these risks in ways that matter for your funds.</p>

        <h5>The "Never Hacked" Claim</h5>
        <p>Kraken has operated since 2011 - making it one of the oldest exchanges still running - without a major security breach. This isn't luck; it's rigorous security architecture. They employ full-time security researchers, run bug bounty programs, and maintain air-gapped cold storage for 95% of assets. The remaining 5% in hot wallets is sufficient for daily operations while minimizing exposure. Every major exchange of Kraken's age has been hacked except Kraken.</p>

        <h5>Proof of Reserves Explained</h5>
        <p>After FTX's collapse revealed customer funds had been misappropriated, proof of reserves became critical. Kraken was an early adopter. Here's how it works: an independent auditor (currently Armanino) verifies that Kraken's on-chain holdings equal or exceed customer deposits. You can cryptographically verify your own balance is included in the audit. This isn't just transparency - it's mathematical proof that your funds exist and are backed 1:1.</p>

        <h5>Regulatory Compliance Benefits</h5>
        <p>Kraken's US registration (FinCEN MSB) and state licenses mean they operate within American law. Benefits: you can confidently use real banking connections, you'll receive proper tax documents (1099s), and you have legal recourse through US courts if problems arise. They also hold FCA registration (UK) and AUSTRAC registration (Australia). This multi-jurisdiction compliance is expensive to maintain - it's part of what you pay for in slightly higher fees.</p>

        <h5>What This Means for You</h5>
        <p>Kraken's security record and compliance posture reduce counterparty risk - the risk that the exchange itself fails or steals your funds. This matters especially for: large balances (the more you hold, the more you should care about security), long-term holders (time increases exposure to exchange risk), and institutional users (fiduciary duties require choosing regulated options). For small trading accounts, the security premium may matter less. For serious crypto wealth, it's invaluable.</p>
